      • collectEntity

        protected void collectEntity(HttpMessage message,
                             java.nio.ByteBuffer inBuf)
                      throws MessageFormatException
        Collect the entity from the ByteBuffer, given its length in contentLength. The entity is returned in the HttpMessage. The buffer position will be advanced by contentLength bytes if successful.
        Parameters:
        message - HttpMessage which we are constructing
        inBuf - ByteBuffer being parsed
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • collectHeaders

        protected void collectHeaders(HttpMessage msg,
                              java.nio.ByteBuffer buf)
                       throws MessageFormatException
        Enter with the cursor (offset) positioned just beyond the end of the first line of an HTTP message. If we are not on an end of line, we should be at the beginning of a colon-delimited header tag. Get the tag, skip the colon and space(s), get the value, skip the end of line, and loop. Continue until the blank line is found or the end of the buffer. Leave the cursor positioned on the blank line marking the end of the header section.
        Parameters:
        msg - HttpMessage being constructed
        buf - ByteBuffer whose contents are being parsed
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • httpEncode

        protected static java.lang.String httpEncode(java.lang.String s)
        The intricacies of Unicode/UTF-8 are ignored. Some sources claim that quite a few more characters need to be encoded. These include: A{1,3,4,5,7}, C{4,5}, E{0,4,5}, C{6,7,9}, E{8,9,C}, D{1,6,8,C,F}, F{1,2,6,9,C} For now, these are ignored too.

      • skipEOL

        protected static int skipEOL(byte[] b,
                             int offset)
                      throws MessageFormatException
        Expect to be positioned on an end of line marker, throwing an exception if not. Skip the end of line marker (any of CR, LF, CRLF), returning the offset after this operation. If the EOL is at the end of the buffer, the value returned will be the length of the buffer.
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • skipToEOL

        protected static int skipToEOL(byte[] b,
                               int offset)
                        throws MessageFormatException
        Expect to be positioned on a non-EOL character; throw an error if the current byte is an EOL. Skip to the first EOL character, returning its offset or -1 if not found.
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • skipToW

        protected static int skipToW(byte[] b,
                             int offset)
                      throws MessageFormatException
        Expect to be positioned on a byte which is neither tab nor space; throw an exception if you are. Skip to the first blank or tab, returning its offset.
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • skipToWorEOL

        protected static int skipToWorEOL(byte[] b,
                                  int offset)
                           throws MessageFormatException
        Expect to be positioned on a byte which is not whitespace (tab, space, CR, LF here); throw an exception if you are. Skip to the first whitespace and return its offset; throw an exception if you can't find one.
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException

      • skipW

        protected static int skipW(byte[] b,
                           int offset)
                    throws MessageFormatException
        Skip to the first byte neither a blank or tab, returning its offset or -1 if not found.
        Throws:
        MessageFormatException - if first byte not whitespace

      • statusLine

        protected static final java.lang.String statusLine(int version,
                                                   int code)
                                            throws IllegalParserStateException
        Given a status code, and knowing the HTTP version number, returns the complete status line in String form. There is at least one anomaly: because there is no HTTP/1.0 300 status code, unrecognized 300 series status codes get turned into the HTTP/1.1 300 status code. Only the pedantic will care ;-)
        Throws:
        IllegalParserStateException
